Visualization of  While normally first to grab a torch and pitchfork and take a run at Excel, UNICEF's single flat file contained more data for less work than both fancy, bespoke data explorers at http://apps.who.int/gho/data/node.main.1097?lang=en and https://public.tableau.com/profile/publish/GNR2015/2015GNR#!/publish-confirm. 

Data similar to that used for http://gamapserver.who.int/gho/interactive_charts/mdg1/atlas.html
But UNICEF's excel files were cleaner and easier to parse, and they already included names and ISO country codes, which will also save time.  

This is a decent data exploration tool, but doesn't tell much of a story. 
http://apps.who.int/gho/data/node.main.1097?lang=en (click through to "interactive graph").  This could use some sprucing up, and I especially wanted to see how stunting has developed over time.  

Why add yet another visualization of childhood malnutrition to the pile? None of the visualizations looked at the trends over time, and I found it difficult to get a sense of how countries and regions compared to one another over time. Another interesting observation is seeing these vital humanitarian measures come "online," as more countries began reporting data. The animated timeseries choropleth is live at the following link. 

Live at [URL TK] Use Jekyll/Github pages. 

If the visualization doesn't fit the browser window correctly, maximize the window to fill the screen. 

Why stunting? Stunting is irrevocable damage malnutrition inflicts on children, and once stunted, children will likely never fully recover.  In human terms, the problem still extends to hundreds of millions of people around the world, though some fervent optimists have still find cause to celebrate the "golden age" the world is enterting. Aldous Huxley once said that doing good was a question of "individual moral craftsmanship," that we must build our own golden age rather than treating it as fait accompli or fatalistically assuming that the human world, the Anthropocene era, must necessarily include food privation.  

Certainly the number of stunted children has gone down significantly on an aggregate basis, though it is equally true that this steep gain has now flattened out.  We can see through the choropleth that stunting has been reduced, though when we segment by region and 



