What might explain this? The Green Revolution introduced across the board yield explosions in grain, courtesy of Norman Borlaug and billions in funding and subsidies for farmer development. Indeed, the World Bank has found that investments in agriculture can yield as much as 200 percent return on investment, dollar for dollar. We see the results of these programs in India and Pakistan, though it's notable that 

UNICEF report: 
http://data.unicef.org/corecode/uploads/document6/uploaded_pdfs/corecode/JME-2015-edition-Sept-2015_203.pdf
This is a story, but .pdfs are static and take effort for humans to read. The two should work together. These infographics are trying to be user friendly, but no reason to dumb things down this much - most of the real data is obscured by the graphics.

The appeal to corporate CSR motivations to invest in nutritional programs to improve marketing is an interesting focus away from the program beneficiaries in the field. To be fair, the report website has a pretty good-looking Tableau instance: http://globalnutritionreport.org/the-data/data-and-visualization-platform/. However, downloading the dataset is frustrating, since it contains only Tableau formatting references, and no numbers. There is a spreadsheet to be had clicking through to https://dataverse.harvard.edu/dataset.xhtml?persistentId=doi:10.7910/DVN/MUOX19, though the list is also confusing.  As an added headache, there are several different variables in each record, with a bunch of categorical strings to muck through once we finally have 001_2015GNRDataset_Child-Adult-Nutrition.xls. 

Further, from what we know from global impact evaluations, we are off target to meet our goals.  From Promise to Impact: Ending
